limit the number of items displayed in the UI. For instance, a grid might display a maximum of 10 items. When fetching new data, any additional items should simply be removed from the view, but not added again.

### Approach

A customized version of the `ListView.builder` widget can be used to limit the items shown. Instead of instantiating a new `ListView.builder` inside the `map` function, a single instance is created and passed along. The `build` function inside `ListView.builder` checks if the count of items has reached or exceeded the limit. If it has, it adds a hidden widget (in this case, an `AppBar`) above the existing ones.

### Implementation with Builder

The following code shows a custom `RecyclerView.builder` designed to implement this behavior:

```dart
class CustomRecyclerBuilder extends StatelessWidget {
  final List<Widget> data; // Existing data
  final Function(int, List<Widget>.ViewChildGetter)> builder;
  final int max = 10;
  CustomRecyclerBuilder({
    Key? key,
    required this.data,
    required this.builder,
  }) : super(key: key);

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    final int count = data.length;
    final List<Widget> children = [
      AppBar(
        title: const Text('Custom Recycler Builder'),
      ),
      ...data
      ].reversed.toList();

    return Scaffold(
      body: Row(
        children: [
          for (int i = 0; i < count; i++)
            i < count && i < max
                ? builder(i, ReorderableListView.builder(
                    padding: const EdgeInsets.all(32),
                    itemCount: count,
                    itemBuilder: (context, index) {
                      return children[index];
                    },
                  ))
                : CustomEmpty(index * max + i),
        ],
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

### Using the `customRecyclerBuilder` Method

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:flutter/widgets.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(const MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyApp({Key? key}) : super(key: key);

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    // Assuming `MyWidget` is some custom widget you want to use as a data item.
    final List<MyWidget> items = []; // Your existing data

    return MaterialApp(
      title: 'Custom Recycler Builder UI',
      theme: ThemeData(primarySwatch: Colors.blue),
      home: CustomRecyclerBuilder(
        data: items,
        builder: (index, child) {
          return ReorderableRowItem(
            index: index,
            child: child,
          );
        },
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

In some scenarios, when fetching data from an API, you might need to use `FutureBuilder`. Here's how you can implement it:

```dart
class MyAppWidget extends StatefulWidget {
  const MyAppWidget({Key? key}) : super(key: key);

  @override
  State<MyAppWidget> createState() => _MyAppWidgetState();
}

class _MyAppWidgetState extends State<MyAppWidget> {
  List<Widget> data = [];

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      body: CustomRecyclerBuilder(
        data: data,
        builder: (index, child) async {
          try {
            final response = await Future.wait([
              http.get(Uri.parse('https://api.example.com/data1')),
              http.get(Uri.parse('https://api.example.com/data2')),
              http.get(Uri.parse('https://api.example.com/data3')),
            ]);
            data = [
              ...response[0].body.parsed(),
              ...response[1].body.parsed(),
              ...response[2].body.parsed(),
            ];
          } catch (e) {
            print(e);
            return const Placeholder();
          }
          return MyWidget();
        },
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

This implementation will prevent the app from being blocked by the network by catching exceptions and returning a `Placeholder` widget if the data fetching fails. It ensures smooth user experience even when there's an issue with the network or the API.

